Referential Actions (in Databases)

Referential Actions are rules applied between related tables (Parent & Child) using Foreign Keys.

They define what happens to child records when the parent record is updated or deleted.

📌 Common Referential Actions:
CASCADE
If parent is deleted → child is deleted automatically
If parent is updated → child updates automatically
👉 Keeps data consistent
SET NULL
If parent is deleted → child foreign key becomes NULL
SET DEFAULT
Child value becomes a default value
RESTRICT / NO ACTION
Prevent deleting parent if related child exists
👉 Protects data from accidental deletion
🧠 Example:
Table: Departments (Parent)
Table: Employees (Child)

| Action   | Result                                   |
| -------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| CASCADE  | All employees deleted                    |
| SET NULL | Employees keep working but no department |
| RESTRICT | ❌ Cannot delete department               |
