DELETE vs TRUNCATE

Both are used to remove data from a table, but they are very different.
| Feature        | DELETE                           | TRUNCATE                       |
| -------------- | -------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Type           | DML (Data Manipulation Language) | DDL (Data Definition Language) |
| Remove         | Specific rows (with WHERE)       | All rows only                  |
| WHERE allowed? | ✅ Yes                            | ❌ No                           |
| Speed          | Slower                           | Very fast                      |
| Rollback       | ✅ Can rollback                   | ❌ Usually cannot rollback      |
| Identity reset | ❌ No                             | ✅ Yes (resets auto-increment)  |
| Triggers       | ✅ Works                          | ❌ Does NOT fire triggers       |

Example:
DELETE:
DELETE FROM Employees
WHERE Salary < 3000;

👉 Deletes only some rows

TRUNCATE:
TRUNCATE TABLE Employees;

👉 Deletes ALL data instantly

🔥 Key Idea (Very Important)
Use DELETE when:
You want to remove specific data
You may need rollback
Use TRUNCATE when:
You want to remove ALL data quickly
You don’t care about rollback or triggers
